text: I get it! Sometimes it's hard to face certain aspects of ourselves.  In horror films it's easier to express certain concepts to understand those aspects. The duality. The conflict within ourselves. I feel that's what this film is about. The intrusive thoughts that weigh us down. The dark side of us. It's that feeling that you get when everything is going so good, and just afraid that something is going to go wrong, and there's nothing that you see that would indicate that but you can feel it, a sense of foreboding. Sometimes for some of us it's how we're always seemingly having bad luck and life just doesn't pan out our way, but maybe if we really look back we can see that in some way we have been self sabotaging our plans, goals, dreams, ideas, lives. I feel like this film is about this. It's subliminal, it's always subliminal in horror films. But that's just what I think.

text: FULL DISCLAIMER:  MY POSTS ARE ONLY FOR PEOPLE WHO LIKE TO READ:  FULL "US" TRAILER REVIEW  REJECTING THE NOMENCLATURE OF WHITE SUPREMACY:  BLACK IMMIGRANTS IN BLACK FACE  Nuance required. I'm with Samuel L. Jackson. Love Peele's storytelling brilliance. Hate Peele's casting decisions -- the routine casting of black immigrants in roles depicting black Americans is very problematic for me and no different than white people in blackface. Black immigrants people are not "black" in their native countries and only become black when they reach American soil. They are only associated with "Us" because of the shared phenotype of melanin.    Black immigrants are replacing black Americans at light-speed in white universities, corporate America and especially Hollywood where even more recently immigrants were cast as Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and his wife Coretta Scott King in the movie Selma. It must be noted that all of the artistic depictions of Dr. King over the last 40 years has been by people outside of his tribe--his statute at the Georgia capitol (white sculptor), his statute as his national memorial in D.C. (Chinese sculptor) and the depiction of him and his wife on film in Selma (British Nigerians). I agree with Nigerian novelist Chimamanda Adichie who says "I want African realities to be explored by Africans." Likewise, I want black American realities explored by black Americans. I also agreed with Ugandan activists who opposed Forrest Whitaker's casting as Idi Amin in "The Last King of Scotland." Black immigrants are not black Americans (and vice versa). They just play "Us" on TV. None of "Us" could go to Nigeria or any part of Africa and enjoy the same rights amongst their people as they enjoy here passing as "Us." Furthermore, Nigerians, in particular, and several other African nations were directly culpable for selling "Us" in to slavery. The thought that "they" can now replace "Us" on film, in the classroom, and in the board room is beyond reprehensible.    Ironically, Jamaican American legal scholar and first tenured "black" woman faculty member at Harvard Law, Lani Guinier, has been writing extensively about the phenomenon of "model" black immigrants replacing "undesirable" black Americans or "preferred blackness." Affirmative Action was not intended for black immigrants but for American Descendants of Slaves (see Executive Orders 10925 and 11246 by Presidents Kennedy and Johnson respectively or President Lyndon Johnson's 1965 Howard University Commencement Address).    Yet people who did not fight our fight are taking the benefits of that fight. Slaves and immigrants should never be confused as members of the same tribe. In many ways the slave was beneath the immigrant. The Trans-Atlantic slave trade was not immigration. It was theft. It was kidnapping. It was torture. It was murder. The immigrant's migration was by choice. The slave's migration was not. The black immigrant fled their country. They did not stay and fight to make their country better. The black immigrant by definition is unpatriotic. The descendant of slaves is by definition the ultimate patriot. The descendant of slaves stayed and fought to make their country better. Black immigrants are runners by definition. Descendants of slaves are fighters. A runner can't lecture a fighter about anything.    The immigrant flees their country to take refuge in another. The descendant of slaves did not leave or abandon their country, but stayed and fought to make its country's Constitutional ideals applicable to them. The latter did not fight to make its country better, but fled to another country to take the rights of people who look like them. This is not an exercise in solidarity, but an exercise in theft. Rejecting white supremacy means rejecting its nomenclature, which assigns group membership based upon melanin or non-melanin content of skin. The inability to think in nuance is what allows black immigrants to "pass" as black Americans or a better terminology American Descendant of Slaves (ADOS). Putting black immigrants in HBCU sweaters does not make them black Americans (ADOS).    Rejecting white supremacy means rejecting its nomenclature, which assigns group membership based upon melanin or non-melanin content of skin. The inability to think in nuance is what allows black immigrants to "pass" as black Americans in the same manner many Jewish people have been afforded the opportunity to "pass" as white Americans. We need a full rejection of the nomenclature of white supremacy. No longer should black immigrants be allowed to claim membership to a group based on melanin content of skin.    We must become more specific in group designations by adding Nigerian American, Caribbean American and others to our job applications, college applications and census forms. No more convoluting all of "Us" into one group based on the magical nonbiological illusion of race or melanin content of skin. No Russian, German, Brit, Scot, Irish, or Frenchman would ever allow you to confuse or convolute all of them into one group based on the lack of melanin in their skin. Likewise, we must reject and abandon the idea of this "one drop" unnuanced grouping of people because of the phenotype of melanin. To do so is to grant authority and legitimacy to white supremacy.    Nevertheless, I applaud Mr. Peele for his unbridled ability to reimagine race on film all while detesting his highly problematic casting decisions. "Get Out" was just the beginning of his genius. Hopefully, "Us" will be the end of his poor casting decisions. Kudos, but critique to Mr. Peele and Merry Christmas and Happy Holidays to all!

text: Couple of things. 1. I got 5 on it. 4 family members. Maybe a 5th?  2. Boy wears a Jaws t-shirt, suggesting he's a horror fan, also hinting at a self aware film?   Also worth noting, he's got a shirt with a piano on it, a stretch , but could be a reference to music being important to the stories plot.  3. Daughter wears a shirt with a bunny on it. Bunnies are really important I guess, but they also multiply like crazy, this could mean multiplicity is related to the story in some sense, or suggesting multiple personality.  4. Scissors look like bunny ears.  5. My take, this movie, is about multiple personality, and a character or lead character is having a mental breakdown, and these visual references are allusions of some sort to the mental break down that person is having.  6. "WE ARE OUR OWN WORST ENEMY." Suggestion they're a threat to themselves, also hinting at multiple personality disorder.  7. I think its the mom whose having the mental break down, but it seems to be from the perspective of the kid. So maybe its about childhood insanity, brought on by trauma maybe the loss of a family member?

text: When life gets rough there's always one thing we can go back to and feel like everything is alright. In my opinion that thing is good music. There have been so many days before when I was younger where everything seemed so overwhelmingly negative... Like there was no light at the end of my tunnel. But then I started listening to my favorite musicians and somehow it made me feel some sort of way... Almost like a hope entered into my life. At that moment I knew what my dream in life was.     I wanted to produce and make music like my favorite artists. I knew I'd never be able to even afford a MIDI keyboard so it stayed a dream, buried deep inside me never to see the light of day. Until now that is. Here I am a few years later and I'm making the music I'd always look for but never could find. This journey in my life has been amazing... And I want to help people feel the same way by listening to the music I create... I wanna be able to make great memories for other people. I want people to hear my music and let it change their day for the better! That's why I started making music. üåå    They're very spacey and futuristic. They make you feel like your life is part of something bigger! It's almost like your being whisked away to another galaxy... I'm not trying to boast. I'm just trying to help you all feel good vibes. And in 2018, I think alot more people need that. If you could help me out by checking my songs it would mean so much. I promise you won't regret it. Thank you for being one of my first fans if you choose to listen. üôè I'll forever remember the first people who supported me... <3

text: That scissor imagery has me thinking this will speak on the consequences of trying to cut out parts of yourself. Obviously, the immediate response is that killing these "clones" is the way to go, but what would that say on a metaphorical level to kill the worst of yourself?     Yeah, you have aspects of yourself that you consider awful but they are still parts of what makes you whole. You need the bad parts of yourself. You need the things that make you fearful. All of that stuff is what fuels the drive to maintain and push forward the best parts of yourself. It is all a balance.     So yeah, I think the "originals" (the little boy is throwing me off though...) might be in for a rude awakening. The same may apply to the "dopplegangers" as well.  I'm there on March 15th!

text: Love, is like a young princess child showing affection for a doll, a doll that she found along the roadside. And this doll was desolate and had one arm torn and missing, and chunks of its hair had melted with the heat, and even worse so, part of her porcelain face had been chipped and broken off; abandoned. However, this young princess saw past all of those scats and defects and leaned down to grab it and held on to it with tender love and care. And she vowed to restore it back to its original condition, and she did. Now, that my friends, is what God has done to us, we, broken vessels, faulty, unfit, and sinful has he chosen to redeem and restore unto perfection so that we may be given a crown of glory in the next life to come. God's love for us is so great that He sent to us His only begotten Son, that we through Him may inherit everlasting life. But sadly, some, like the doll, will not respond to God's love and kindness.  www.ourforgiveness.com    -All glory be given to God.

text: Well there are some hints/allusions and interesting moments in a trailer.... 1. 1:40 moment. Who is this girl? This beach is the same like before (0:47). Their daughter is not so young, so it can be young Adelaide. cause "Haunted by an unexplainable and unresolved trauma from her past and compounded by a string of eerie coincidences, Adelaide feels her paranoia elevate to high-alert as she grows increasingly " It means Adelaide already met her Dark Doppelganger when she was young. And this beach can be some kind of starting point of this nightmare... Like mind trigger. 2. Song meaning. A lot of drug/dope meanings also connected with Lab Rabbits in cages which reminds of some experiments with people (Like in "Get out" movie). Like they are just "guinea pigs" of some trial. 3. Everybody dies around, but they are safe all the time. "If you want to get crazy, we can get crazy." Depends on who are "you" and who are "we" this one can take one more meaning. 4. Mask on their son. He looks pretty sticked to it and it looks very unnatural. 5. Scissors - symbol of life and death. At the same time they mean union (the two parts act as one) and the gap (they cut the thread of life). The attribute of the Greek goddess of fate, Moira Atropos. Atropos was the oldest of the Three Fates, and was known as the "inflexible" or "inevitable." It was Atropos who chose the mechanism of death and ended the life of mortals by cutting their thread with her "abhorred shears"

text: I think they are one in the same, and of course it comes across as these being mimic imposters but what if neither are what they appear to be. We assume from this trailer the family is being stalked by these entities but what if everyone's perception is warped? This seems like such a crazy twist on duality and has an almost modern Dr.Jekyll and Mr.Hyde vibe to it. Knowing Peele everyone might be super wrong on all these theories, but I definitely believe there is something very strange about Lupita's character and the son. The vibes from them seem completely different than the older sister and the father and then the little girl doesn't seem to be part of the family so who exactly js she? Could it be the mother and son are actually  the "imposters" and now these "twin" entities are there to reveal that? So many thoughts going through my head. That's how you know it's a phenomenal trailer when it is this thought provoking. Super excited for this.

text: Just my thoughts. The ‚Äúhorror‚Äù family in fact is NOT the family chasing the protagonists, but the protagonists themselves. This film IMO is about how we as black people attempt to bury/supress our roots/past in the quest for white upward mobility. The dialogue in the car and subsequent signs of upward mobility (the boat, the vacation etc.) teases this. This appears to be a film about how we will grow up in the hood, attend tough urban public schools, and go to HBCU‚Äôs, only to try and bury that past by moving to exclusive white neighborhoods and sending our kids to white private schools. Yet, we will quietly continue to appropriate and consume black urban culture (as documented in how the parents ironically talk about not doing drugs to the kids,  all while listening to a classic hip-hop song....that glorifies drug use. Looks interesting; I will definitely see this.

text: I know this comment has nothing to be with the message but it is very important for you.  the Prince of Peace, is the only One who can give us unshakable peace in a world of turmoil. As someone said, "There will never be peace in the individual heart or at the peace tables of the world until the Prince of Peace reigns supreme in the hearts of men." Jesus said, "Peace I leave with you; my peace I give to you. I do not give to you as the world gives. Do not let your hearts be troubled and do not be afraid"(John 14:27). He also said, "Come to me, all you who are weary and burdened, and I will give you rest"(Matthew 11:28)My Friend: I am asking you the most important question of life. Your joy or your sorrow for all eternity depends upon your answer. The question is: Are you saved? It is not a question of how good you are, nor if you are a church member, but are you saved? Are you sure you will go to Heaven when you die?  God says in order to go to Heaven, you must be born again. In John 3:7, Jesus said to Nicodemus, ‚ÄúYe must be born again.‚Äù  In the Bible God gives us the plan of how to be born again which means to be saved. His plan is simple! You can be saved today. How?  First, my friend, you must realize you are a sinner. ‚ÄúFor all have sinned, and come short of the glory of God‚Äù(Romans 3:23).  Because you are a sinner, you are condemned to death. ‚ÄúFor the wages [payment] of sin is death‚Äù (Romans 6:23). This includes eternal separation from God in Hell.  ‚Äú . . . it is appointed unto men once to die, but after this the judgment‚Äù (Hebrews 9:27).  But God loved you so much He gave His only begotten Son, Jesus, to bear your sin and die in your place. ‚Äú . . . He hath made Him ] to be sin for us . . . that we might be made the righteousness of God in Him‚Äù (2 Corinthians 5:21).  Jesus had to shed His blood and die. ‚ÄúFor the life of the flesh is in the blood‚Äù (Lev. 17:11). ‚Äú . . . without shedding of blood is no remission [pardon]‚Äù (Hebrews 9:22).  ‚Äú . . . God commendeth His love toward us, in that, while we were yet sinners, Christ died for us‚Äù (Romans 5:8).  Although we cannot understand how, God said my sins and your sins were laid upon Jesus and He died in our place. He became our substitute. It is true. God cannot lie.  My friend, ‚ÄúGod . . . commandeth all men everywhere to repent‚Äù (Acts 17:30). This repentance is a change of mind that agrees with God that one is a sinner, and also agrees with what Jesus did for us on the Cross.  In Acts 16:30-31, the Philippian jailer asked Paul and Silas: ‚Äú . . . ‚ÄòSirs, what must I do to be saved?‚Äô And they said, ‚ÄòBelieve on the Lord Jesus Christ, and thou shalt be saved . . . .‚Äô ‚Äù  Simply believe on Him as the one who bore your sin, died in your place, was buried, and whom God resurrected. His resurrection powerfully assures that the believer can claim everlasting life when Jesus is received as Savior.  ‚ÄúBut as many as received Him, to them gave He power to become the sons of God, even to them that believe on His name‚Äù (John 1:12).  ‚ÄúFor whosoever shall call upon the name of the Lord shall be saved.‚Äù (Romans 10:13).  Whosoever includes you. Shall be saved means not maybe, nor can, but shall be saved.  Surely, you realize you are a sinner. Right now, wherever you are, repenting, lift your heart to God in prayer.  In Luke 18:13, the sinner prayed: ‚ÄúGod be merciful to me a sinner.‚Äù Just pray: ‚ÄúOh God, I know I am a sinner. I believe Jesus was my substitute when He died on the Cross. I believe His shed blood, death, burial, and resurrection were for me. I now receive Him as my Savior. I thank You for the forgiveness of my sins, the gift of salvation and everlasting life, because of Your merciful grace. Amen.‚Äù  Just take God at His word and claim His salvation by faith. Believe, and you will be saved. No church, no lodge, no good works can save you. Remember, God does the saving. All of it!  God‚Äôs simple plan of salvation is: You are a sinner. Therefore, unless you believe on Jesus Who died in your place, you will spend eternity in Hell. If you believe on Him as your crucified, buried, and risen Savior, you receive forgiveness for all of your sins and His gift of eternal salvation by faith.  You say, ‚ÄúSurely, it cannot be that simple.‚Äù Yes, that simple! It is scriptural. It is God‚Äôs plan. My friend, believe on Jesus and receive Him as Savior today.  If His plan is not perfectly clear, read this tract over and over, without laying it down, until you understand it.Your soul is worth more than all the world.  ‚ÄúFor what shall it profit a man, if he shall gain the whole world and lose his own soul?‚Äù (Mark 8:36).  Be sure you are saved. If you lose your soul, you miss Heaven and lose all. Please! Let God save you this very moment.  God‚Äôs power will save you, keep you saved, and enable you to live a victorious Christian life. ‚ÄúThere hath no temptation taken you but such as is common to man: but God is faithful, Who will not suffer you to be tempted above that ye are able; but will with the temptation also make a way to escape, that ye may be able to bear it‚Äù(1 Corinthians 10:13).

text: (REPENTANCE is required to be hidden from the Lords anger/JUDGMENT DAY!):  Seek ye the LORD,  all ye meek of the earth,  who have upheld his justice;  seek righteousness,  seek meekness:  it may be ye  shall be hid  in the day of the LORD'S anger.  (Zephaniah 2:3).  ***(Seek The Lord): This is the language of true (REPENTANCE), renewal, and regeneration.  ***(You will be hidden): Zephaniah used a play on words with meaning of his own name, "Hidden in the Lord." Even in the midst of the most calamitous judgment scenes, the mercy and grace of the Lord is still available to a (REPENTANT) people.  ***(Luke 13:3)<---Jesus)<---I tell you, Nay: but, except ye (REPENT), ye shall all likewise perish.  ***(Luke 5:32)<---(Jesus)<---I came not to call the righteous, but sinners to (REPENTANCE).  ***(2 Peter 3:9)<---The Lord is not slack concerning his promise, as some men count slackness; but is longsuffering to us-ward, not willing that any should perish, but that all should come to (REPENTANCE).  ***(Romans 2:4)<---Or do you disregard the riches of His kindness, tolerance, and patience, not realizing that God's kindness leads you to (REPENTANCE?)  *** (REPENTANCE):  (Greek. Metanoia); Strong's #3341; This Greek word is a compound word derived from meta, meaning "after" and suggesting some type of change, and nous, meaning "mind."   Thus the word strictly denotes "a change of mind."  But it also connotes remorse for sin, accompanied by a desire to turn away from one's sin, to God, for salvation.  Both John the Baptist and Jesus began their ministries with a call to repentance. (See Matthew 3:2, 4:17)---A call that many of the social outcasts and "sinners" of that day answered, (See Luke 19:1-10),  but that the religious people rejected. (Luke 11:39-44; 18:9-14).

text: I have a feeling that the fun house on the beach might have a lot to do with the story here. It has a giant sign that says "find yourself" where the clone appears and it seems like this is where pigtail girl wanders in to find "herself". It seems like it's some portal to another plane or dimension where copies can body snatch their clones. There's also a lot of subtle allusion to mirrors and glass and thread and cutting and breaking. Also there's a quick glimpse of the lost souls wandering the halls during the chase for pigtail girl. It's such an interesting concept about self and subconscious and reality I've wondered why more people haven't explored this idea like this. I really wanna see how the rabbits play into it. It reminds me of a few movies where people are led astray and turned into beasts.

text: Notes: 1) the image of black ink on white backgrounds make Rorschach tests, which are made by folding a piece of paper with ink on it to make a parallel symmetrical image to be analyzed to understand a person‚Äôs perspective.  2) The paper men and scissors are a mirror image of something created once but creates many. Even the scissors are symmetrical, scissors are just two blades with handles kept together by one joint or screw.  3) The white rabbits are likely an allusion to some of the earliest tests of genetic cloning. Perhaps the black people seen in the same hallway are parallels to the white rabbits.  4) This movie is definitely about having multiple identities or personalities or even different ideas of a person in your mind than what is perceived. There can be a different you that someone knows that is nothing like the you that they know or that you even know.   This trailer alone has me so excited, been waiting for Jordan Peele to follow up to Get Out and this looks great. He‚Äôs always been great with relating to black issues, with Key and Peele he did it in comedy. Now, he‚Äôs doing it with horror. With his own great style. Brilliant mind!

text: THESE ARE ALL JUST THEORIES, DON'T TAKE MY WORD FOR FACT  1:55 notice how there are figures wearing red and standing in front of the beach which is shown to be strewn with unconscious or, more likely, dead bodies behind them. Also notice how the figures are all white here. The unconscious/dead bodies behind them could more than likely be the original persons. Yet the bright red jumpsuit, leather fingerless glove, and oddly shaped scissors still are there. Maybe the protagonist family aren't the only ones with doppelg√§ngers?  2:08 white lady's got a glove and scissors and more than likely one of those red jumpsuits. Chances are, this too is a clone who kills the white  lady with our protagonists shown on the beach.  Another thing is that Jordan Peele said there would be NO racial undertones about this movie, so I wouldn't go so far as to say that the white friends of the family are the antagonists. After all, the deeper meaning of this film, as stated in the trailer, is "We are our own worst enemies."  2:24 we have a shot of Adelaide (Nyong'o's character) in a classroom-type setting with her doppelg√§nger, and there's one long drawing of stick figures holding hands behind the doppelg√§nger. This could mean that the doppelg√§nger is trying to explain that it's not just them who have clones, but way more than them. This could be justified by the white lady seen with scissors, the glove, and the jumpsuit just some seconds earlier in the trailer and before THAT, the white lady friend crawling on the ground, appearing to be dying. Additionally, Adelaide's doppelg√§nger is holding the scissors and also two figures of people who are initially holding hands, only for the double to pull them away, possibly showing and symbolizing that the doubles want to separate their respective persons and take over their lives, or something to that effect.

text: Whatever is going on in this trailer, it appears to be some kind of city-wide panic. In numerous shots, the backgrounds are littered with bodies, and the "good" family are moving around the central beach town being chased by their clones. Considering that we never blatantly see anyone else's clone except for the family's, we could maybe say that it's them that committed what appears to be a mass murder, but in 0:44 you can see the bloody white man on the beach is wearing a red jumpsuit under his cloak(the same jumpsuit the family is wearing) so that probably means it is some kind of mass attack of doppelgangers (I think the reason he is on the beach, just standing there is because he has already killed his "original" hence his being bloody, and now does not know what to do. This would also explain why you never see the family being attacked by anyone else's doppelganger, and even the family's appear to be attacking only the member they are clones of). My theory is that the entire "good" family are clones and the "bad" family are their originals, and all the people in this mysteriously secluded beach town are clones. Their original, evil selves are attacking the town after escaping from the place they were held at. There is however the possibility of something deeper than just cloning, like an alternate universe, as their is no way for the "evil" masked little boy clone to know his "good" counterpart is also wearing a mask, which is what he shows up to the house in. The lightning storm we are shown at 1:01 could be how they get into our dimension.  The rabbits signify cloning, as they are frequently cloned in the name of science. This may be some kind of experiment run by the community in "Get Out," it could be them cloning the same evil person and then stealing their body, making them good, wiping out their own memories, and then being attacked by the mind-broken original person, but the fact that their are several white people dead on the streets, as well as a white woman being attacked at 1:59 discredits this, but if you pause the video at 2:08 you see her doppelganger wearing a red top, and it also appears to be in the same scene where she's being attacked, meaning it is most likely a mass attack of clones. Another thing I noticed, the daughter is wearing a rabbit shirt, if you pause the clip at 0:36 you'll see that.

text: Amazing!!!  This is how to make a Black Horror Film.  It isn't pandering or exploitation, it is earnest characteristics and characterizations.  That is how you make it with Black people, without making it about them being Black.  I appreciated Get Out, for how it exploited that weakness in Black characters in Film and in American Life period, but although it was necessary to create that film, this one seems to be allowing the characters to exist without including a foil based on Racial points.  They are a Black Family and encounter a Horrific plot that should be enjoyable and suspenseful whether or not it was a family of a different race.  Usually Black Horror Films have to rely on the same traits as any Predominantly Black Film, and its worst trait is Over Blackifying every element of an otherwise traditional story and sometimes worse create a Homebrew Blackified Plot Device that wouldn't be used in any other instance because it doesn't make sense.  Like Soul Plane.  I love the Wayans because they subject that treatment in Parody and Slapstick, which makes perfect sense for those elements, but the film's they are criticising like Blaxploitation films usually implemented stereotypes just as flagrantly but there was no Satire at all.

They refer to cutting a life thread, but they also represent the union of spiritual and physical.  Then we have the rabbits : Rabbits are also a symbol of fertility, family and new life. ... Symbolic rabbit meanings deal primarily with abundance, comfort, and vulnerability. Traditionally, rabbits are associated with fertility, sentiment, desire, and procreation.  We also have the color red in the outfits of the  Doubleganger family  That looks a lot like the outfit in the handmaid's tale  An interesting Lee in love he has Elisabeth moss and the cast.  That outfit is a symbol of oppression and that that dystopia.   Maybe it symbolizes what the trailer says how we are our own worst enemies and hold ourself back and oppress ourselves even more. Even the song he chose. I don't know I'm super intrigued by this movie I love that is a black family in the front and I think it's gonna be a social commentary on the mental issues that we are having nowadays so potently.  I can't wait to see it I personally will now see a second trailer because I wanna watch the movie with the little info that I have right now and that's it. text: I'm liking the symbolism from the scissors. A lot of people are referring to what scissors do which is cut things, but I'm thinking it has to do with what scissors are. I mean it's why scissors is a singular item but referred to as a plural. Because really scissors are two blades put together to form one object. They are just a blade when separate but when two identical blades are put together like that they become an entirely new object that fulfills an entirely new purpose. I think that has a lot more relevance to what the movie is going to be doing than cutting things apart.

text: This looks like it's about how we are our own worst enemies. We are constantly battling that part of ourselves that self destructs. That part of ourselves that says the worst and the cruellest things that no one else ever would. Each day we battle with it and each day one side wins. Which side kills the other for today? Am I going to be my true self today or am I going to be my self-loathing self-destructive self today?   Edit:  I just wanted to add that I read that Jordan Peele said that racism isn't the focus of this film (although I'm sure it's a part of it) but that being our worst enemies is. For instance I noticed that Lupita's Doppelganger has natural afro-american short hair, no makeup and a bit of an accent. It seems almost like her "worst enemy" is largely her culture and natural self. In the trailer Lupita's character is sort of out of place from the beginning. In the car ride she is moving off beat to the song almost like it's saying that she's not in sync with herself. The way she's sitting in the car feels out of place and kind of uncomfortable too, like she's just not comfortable in her own skin. That's the feeling I got the whole time watching the trailer. Then her Doppelganger is so stark in contrast to her that it just feels like she's repressing parts of herself and is anglo-americanizing/white washing herself. Also, her Doppelganger's face kind of looks like a puppet. Sort of like black face. The way whites represented blacks in media as empty shells that were just the whites' stereotypical versions of them. Lupita's Doppelganger even has the 'black face slave voice'. Then the boy is wearing a literal mask on his head for most of the movie and his Doppelganger is wearing a creepy mask over himself in the whole trailer. Which makes me think that the boy is wearing a symbolic mask throughout his life. He's not showing his true self and he's hiding behind his mask to protect himself. Plus, the boy's mask is literally a monkey/ape. Just more racist symbolism.Later in the trailer we see his Doppelganger without his mask and his mouth has scars from being burnt. To me that's saying that the boy feels like his voice is not heard. That he is either unworthy of being listened to or that what he says makes him unworthy. I cant tell which until I see the movie. It probably showed up after some kind of childhood trauma. Similarly if the Doppelganger's mouth is not burnt closed, it could also mean that he was emotionally scarred and that caused him to retreat into his mask. So to me it seems that the Doppelgangers are initially their enemies, their self-loathing self-destructors... but they're also confronting them with the reality of what they've disconnected from themselves. Lupita's Doppelganger that symbolizes the whites' black face/puppet version of afro-americans is confronting Lupita with the fact that she is now doing this to herself to feel more worthy. She is anglo-americanizing herself. The Doppelgangers are confronting them with what they're suppressing most, and what they're hiding about themselves that they ultimately HATE MOST about themselves. Which is in turn what the Doppelgangers are. So not only are the Doppelgangers that inner part of themselves that hate themselves the most, but they are also WHAT they hate the most about themselves. That's the symbolism of the scissors in my opinion. They are literally cutting out aspects of themselves that they deem to be unworthy.

text: Things of significance in this trailer: Mask Bunny Beach Scissors The mask could represent different personalities, hiding the truth, covering something up. Bunnies, as many people have said cloning. And what they typically use bunnies for it testing, it seemed the duplicates all had some kind of healed injury so maybe these families were cloned (willingly or not?) and the duplicates escaped and are seeking revenge because they had to be subjected to a life of torture while the originals got to live in bliss (beach house, boat, happy family). The beach..... I guess that could be new beginnings, tides wash away the sand kind of deal. I don't know what else the beach could represent.  Scissors. All of them had scissors and they seemed to be the only thing they were really using to attack. But I'm not sure what they could represent, if anything, but I feel like Jordan Peele wouldn't put something like that and have it NOT have meaning. Apparently Peele said this was going to be a new horror movie "villain", so cloning and evil twins or doppelgangers seems a bit on the nose. BUT, it seems that directors have very little say in what's shown in trailers, so this might have given away more than he wanted it to.

So plot flow is probably she discovered the things and where they come from as a young girl but the trauma of almost being killed by her clone makes her blot it out. text: Okay, I've seen everyone's ideas, and I'm gonna try to mold mine together based off of them. I think the scissors represent the negative alter egos (other family) trying to cut off the cultural appropriation of the "normal" family. They seem like the type of family that surrounds themselves around Caucasians to increase their social status, when in reality their only cutting away from their African roots. I think the other family is trying to like, idk cut off that "whiteness" within the normal family, making them truly black again.  Or this could be a low-key statement of how the real part of African Americans try to cut off all of the stereotypes and expectations set by white America. Thus, being the reason why the normal family hangs out with the white people.  Another theory I have is that the other family is the future. Like, if the normal family continued disregarding their roots. Because like another commenter said, the little boy has a whit face. I interpret this as the kid is the furthest away from his culture, thus being seen as "white" (also this ties into the stigma of if a black kid is raised well, he's seen white as his peers because he has adaquat home training) The daughter has straight hair, and this reminds me of the black girl that went on Dr.Phil  and said she was white. So this is what I mean by the normals will become the family with scissor hands. The mom does a and movement when she taps her face, and that's a sign of poshness (or so I've heard) Now the dad, I'm not too sure of, and I'd love for the movie to go further into him.  Longest story short, I think the "killer" family is trying to stop their past selves from turning into literal monsters, by cutting out the socializing and trying to be white. EDIT------ I found out the other family members are called the tethered, which further proves what I was saying about them being a tether to their roots Also, I believe I said that the other family are counterparts, but I'll say it again now. The mother never smiles, but the tethered version is always happy to the point it's weird. The real dad is always cracking dad jokes n stuff, but the tethered is serious. The daughter cares about her image, the tethered one DOESN'T EVEN HAVE EYEBROWS!!! And the son talks too much, the other one doesn't speak at all. The scissors are like a thing to connect the both of them (the tethered and the real family) as one. That way they'll be a better person, because they're not a good people without their flaws, of which they've CUT off of themselves

Or they could just be their deepest darkest feelings and emotions that have manifested into a person that now wants to destroy them so they can act out these negative feelings & emotions instead of hiding them like the original family maybe has. Either way the Tethered are their direct opposites as the mom seems to be more serious and structured while her Tethered version runs down the hall with scissors which when a person partakes in is said ‚Äúto willfully act in a reckless, foolish, and/or dangerous manner‚Äù. Tethered means to be tied so I think the purpose of the scissors is to untether or untie themselves from the family we see so there is no more ties and instead of two versions there will only be one in the end and the Tethered want to be the surviving ones. The rabbits made me think cloning but also made me think of Alice in Wonderland like going down the rabbit hole which is defined as ‚Äúused to refer to a bizarre, confusing, or nonsensical situation or environment, typically one from which it is difficult to extricate oneself.‚Äù So perhaps the ride saying ‚ÄúFind Yourself‚Äù with the mirrors inside is actually a ‚Äúrabbit hole‚Äù that leads to the hallway/mental hospital and the Tethered or ‚Äúrabbits‚Äù dwell there but have escaped. In the scene with the little girl in that hallway, she & the people behind her look like they were all on the beach and all went on that ride or a ride down the rabbit hole to where their true selfs are.

text: He already said that it isn't about race but I've watched this trailer so much that I've noticed some things. The youngest girl in the trailer isn't part of the family and is most likely a flashback to an earlier incident that happened to provide some type of background story. Also in the present the younger boy seems to wander off just like the little girl we see on the beach. I believe that connects. I feel like children play a big part in this story. Maybe the youngest child being the easiest to manipulate. I'm not sure. Also, the doppelg√§ngers all carry scissors as their weapons. In Jordan Peele's movie posters for the movies it says "Join the untethering." I assume the doppelg√§ngers want freedom from something. I am not sure what. They all also wear gloves on their right hands. Don't know what it means but I am sure that it has something to do with the bloody handprints that we see on the wall of the classroom at 2:23 and on the clothes of the people at 1:54 . Also in that same scene, the people that Lupita wants to kill are holding hands and scissors at the same time. Why does she want to kill them? There is a child in the middle of them. That's weird. Also in the classroom there are stick figures holding hands drawn on the board behind Lupita's doppelg√§nger. Why? I can't figure it out but maybe some of you guys can. I'm very intrigued on what he means by "the untethering." There's some type of tether that the doppelg√§ngers want to sever.

text: Over the past few years I've frequently ranted about all the creepy/dramatic slowed-down covers of popular songs in movie trailers. I said they've been done to death, they have no impact anymore, there's too many of them, they've lost their power quickly and it's been a parody of itself for a few years now.  I can't believe I'm saying this but I was so wrong. THIS creepy slowed-down cover of a popular song in a movie trailer is brilliant and terrifying and just thinking about it gives me chills. I freakin' love it. It turns out there's still life in the old slow cover song trailer trend yet.  Bravo, Mr. Peele. Bravo.

text: While I don't think this will definitely be what the film is about, I believe that the film explores such topics as genetic splicing and cloning. Genetic splicing refers to when the DNA of an organism is cut, and a gene from another organism is then inserted. While this is often used to make things like insulin, I feel that what Us does speak about it. In the trailer, the Wilson family goes out on vacation to get away from it all, only to have their home get invaded by intruders. What may seem to be just your average home invasion movie is suddenly dropped on its head where the strangers reveal themselves as being near spitting replicas of the Wilsons. Doppelgangers are traditionally understood to be the look-alikes of people, often with their being a supernatural reason behind it. It is always said that if you were to see your doppelganger, that would mark you for death. Famous people in history such as Abraham Lincoln reported seeing two versions of themselves in mirrors.   These doppelgangers in this case are given the name "The Tethered." Tethered refers to a rope or chain which is used to tie an animal to restrict its movement. In the trailer, you notice that the doppelgangers of the Wilson family move in animalistic ways such as by getting into trees to ambush the family or growling at them. In short, they act beastly. However, as many have noted, the Tethered are not perfect replicas of the Wilsons at all. One child has noticeable burn marks on his face that he hides beneath a mask. The other members of the Tethered "family" seem to be unable to speak except for one. While they are able to know what their counterparts would behave and the moves they would make, the problem is that they seemed to be undercooked. As if being "restrained" in their movements.  As for the whole idea on gene splicing, I feel that the Tethered were born from human DNA being extracted from the family members (most likely without their knowledge), and then a gene is inserted. I also kind of think that the recurring theme of scissors is a visual metaphor for genetic splicing, but I digress.  I am basing that idea off of how the synopsis of the film makes it clear that Mrs. Wilson had a traumatic experience sometime in her life. Could it be that she was experimented on by being impregnated for whatever purpose? I am aware that many are trying to automatically connect Us with Peele's Get Out, but I feel that the two are unrelated. In Us, I feel that instead of the Armitage family, you could have a secret facility trying to create perfect clones for whatever reason. While I know that Jordan Peele said that there wouldn't be any "race" related subject matter in the film, he does make it clear that the movies each serve as social commentary. So, it could refer to anything.   As for why I believe that the Tethered are clones, there's a moment in the trailer where Mrs. Wilson was in what appeared to be a research facility and you see numerous rabbits throughout the facility. Rabbits are known as being some of the primary guinea pigs when it comes to research. In 2002, French scientists were able to produce the first cloned rabbit using the ovum cumulus cells from a female rabbit. Also, rabbits are known for reproducing quickly, so there's that.

text: I believe the mom is a clone that successfully switched with her original self as a little girl. The seen on the beach with the little girl walking looked like a flash back. This could have been from the clones memory showing what she did to the "real" little girl, which we see something similar with the son at the beach. She's also the one that said we have to kill them before they kill us (maybe a hint at her previous experience). The cut out paper towards the end of the clip shows 2 girls further emphasizing clones. You would assume clones can't be perfect so they may not do everything identical, so when we see her snapping her fingers to the music and you can easily tell that she's off rhythm. Also they further emphasize this when they show the clones trying to talk like the original family members but obviously sound different. It's like she's been living as the real girl for so long to where it almost looks convincing but she still shows the flaws in being an imperfect clone. When she's at the beach sitting next to the people she starts moving kind of weird like she's malfunctioning or something. Someone else has a theory about schizophrenia which is interesting too. I'm curious to know if you have your own theories too. Please feel free to add to the conversation. I just heard about this movie today but it looks pretty cool so far. text: I don't get why people think the red suit wearing clones are the originals when they act very psychotic and crazy, like they are having fun tormenting the original family in ways that show that they are not the real ones and just want to kill and replace them. Like, didn't we see the Tethered of Jason walk in fire then out unfazed by it and even goading Adelaide? This is biggest indication that this horror movie isn't gonna end with the cliche of "Uh oh they were the clones all along." And before anyone comes and say, "But Jason's Tethered has burn scars on his face!" I know. But I think the mask he's wearing is fire proof and to hide that his disfigurement from people when he replaces the Original Jason. Also, I will say this again, the way the trailer showed it made it seem like Adelaide tried to kill him and it showed that she is unable to kill him, meaning that Jason might have to kill him...or maybe the twist ending is that Jason will end being the fake because the mask would do well in hiding his face and putting Adelaide into a false sense of security? Either way, what I'm getting at is that Peele has even stated that those four in the red jumpsuits are called the Tethered so, it wouldn't really make sense for the Tethered of the family to be the "real" family. Especially with how they act...they are literally tormenting the family and playing with them before they kill them except for Gabe's Tethered who is shown to be stone-faced or angry. The exact opposite of Gabe. And with how they are introduced, you really expect me to believe that "The ones in the jumpsuits were the real people all along" when the doppelganger of Jason crawls on all fours, the doppelganger of Zora simply walks and is then shown fastly climbing a tree and getting in through Zora's bedroom window probably, and Adelaide's, who is the little girl meaning that they know each other, is sitting weirdly on a chair. If they were the originals why even try this creepy stuff if they wanted to get their life back, just simply kill them if that were the case.  I hope Nobody takes this as insulting, but the number of comments saying that they theorize that these red suited ones are the originals is way too much and it just doesn't work with the way that they acted and the way they torture the Wilsons. What should be questioned is "Why are they all wearing that glove  on their right hand?" "Where do the Tethered come from since Adelaide encountered her's in her youth?" "What's the meaning behind the rabbits?" I want see theories about that for this movie because this trailer just instantly debunks ALL the "The clones were the originals and the family we saw are the clones" theories because of the the Tethered's personalities and because it seems that you can only kill YOUR Tethered.

text: Theory: The mother knows about the clones because she is a self aware clone herself. She realized this when she was younger (little girl with thriller shirt sending some flashback types of vibes).    Her family doesn't know that she's an self aware clone, but the bitter truth is that a secret organization within the government have been cloning people that had already *Died* in order to preserve human population.   Due to some clones becoming self aware, it slowly becomes a domino effect where now the most recent clones are coming to kill off the previous clones and to take their respective roles within society. They're also planning to end cloning once they're done with the massacre. Lupita had already died years ago, but her DNA (from being collected by the govt) was able to make a clone out of her. Now usually they will make it where the clones forget their previous memories, but we all know that mistakes can happen and sometimes technology have *errors.* Well in this case, Lupita was the aftermath of that error. The error of getting her previous memories back, which is why that beach scene of her is highly significant to the movie.    Something I think Jordan Peele would consider doing something like this.

text: I think the theory of the messed up family being the originals seems the most plausible since the white lady talks about the kids like they were grown. The way she says "i can't believe how big they are" strikes me as odd. I also believe the rabbits are going to be how they are grown which is why there's a big emphasis on the rabbits. Another thing I've noticed it the way the mother holds the children when they are under attack. She holds the kids in front of her instead of behind her. What kind of mother puts her kids directly in danger? The mother is protecting the kids like they are valuable test subjects instead of her actual children.  One more theory that seems plausible is the one where the original family died a long time ago and the clones we see are another generation of failed experiments. So there are no originals its just copies fighting to be what they think is the original.

text: Thoughts on the use of "Five on It"  The song is undoubtedly about the sale and use of weed. The father denies this and ironically calls it a "dope" song. It would be easy to dismiss this as a dad protecting his naive little boy. What I find disturbing is that this is the father is flat out lying.  I think denial is going to be playing a large part in this film. Denial of trauma, of reality, of one's true self. The little boy that was lied to wears a mask for God's sake. I think it's going to be about people who may not be comfortable in their own skin, so their true selves got their own skin, and are now here to confront their hypocritical counterparts.

text: Alright.. this + the Superbowl ad's got me thinking what the symbolism is here...    It's like there's this "Black Cloud" hanging over us...  was a quote Lupita said in the Superbowl trailer...   The symbolism with that line when it comes to how some  Black People/Minorities feel in America sometimes.  As if their blackness will somehow hold them back in life due to the perception, and thus feel the need to try to come off as "safer" or less "controversial" or more "tolerant" of the way they've been treated, because they are afraid if they act themselves, that they will be perceived in some sort of negative light.        Then in the opposite spectrum, you have other people whom are considered "not black enough" because they portray themselves as the opposite of the "stereotype".  You usually hear this with someone whom is considered well educated, punctual or well-spoken.  This is essentially those people's way of saying that if you are "Black" you are not allowed to be these things or you're abnormal, and if you are it's seen as an attribute unexpected of you due to your "blackness".       How often do you see a Black Athlete where the news media will always say in terms of an attribute, or benefit "He's softspoken." or "he's well-spoken" as if it's a credit for them but you never hear that given to a white athlete as a 'benefit'.  Because the black athlete isn't "expected" to speak "properly".    It's actually an insult that someone goes "wow you're so well-spoken." as if that's a + rather than the expectation.     That "Black Cloud" has so many meanings, particularly in shaping how the "minority in america" is 'supposed' to act, and how some feel they're 'forced' to act, just to 'fit into it'.  A layer that society makes you feel you have to "cut away(scissors symbolism)" in order to make it, or be perceived as 'not a threat.'.   Look at how Lupita's hair is the extension dreads, while her 'doppelganger is much more akin to wearing it natural and closer to her roots.   The duality between the 'clones' and the main characters, seems to be something the movie will hit home on.      It's as if it's saying that some black people grow up feeling like if they are going to fit into society and be perceived as not a threat, that they have to 'sever' whatever the perception of 'black' is away from themselves.   It's sad, how true that is in some cases.   That mentality, of stripping away that side of yourself in order to fit in, captures the duality between these clones and the family.  And it hits home how further and further, with each passing year, so many black people or other minorities, stray away from their roots in order to attempt to 'blend' into a society that didn't have to shed theirs for their benefit.     The biggest nightmare, is feeling you need to run away from yourself, in order to be *allowed* to flourish...     So then the question becomes...are the family we spend time with most of the movie really themselves...or are *they* the clones. Think about it.       Peele with that symbolism again, and the fact he's using a dark skinned cast to hit home this point in Hollywood makes it all the more clear, when you consider the stigma around it in Hollywood, and in general.

text: Here's my theory (inspired by other observers): This movie will take place in past and present in which the tethers origins are explained. I say past, because the mom knew of the impending danger before the imposters invaded their home (or at least I think she said that before they got in). She also freaked out about losing Jason at the beach, where kids would normally be allowed to run around alone for a bit, like she didn't want to lose Jason to their clones. Also, when Jason sees one of the tethers at the beach, it already has blood on its hands, meaning the beach takes place in the future. Furthermore, as the trailer progresses, the environment gets worse in the scenes featuring the beach, hence supporting my theory that the beach is in the future. Now here comes the part that was inspired by other viewers: the rabbits represent a duality. Rabbits are a prominent symbol in the teasers, which mean they have a HUGE meaning for the story. Rabbits may symbolize innocence, but they are also known to be the opposite. We see scenes of a lab with rabbits on the loose. In that same area, the younger daughter (clone) walks around with a crazed smile and no one seems to care. She also seems to mind her own business otherwise she would've killed anyone passing by her. The relationship with the lab and the girl indicates there's an essence of familiarity (I say familiar, because we see the lab possibly in the future, when the real mom walks in and prepares to attack anything with a bat only to see a bunch of rabbits released) and will explain the origins of the tethers. I propose the rabbits were part of a cloning experiment that went horribly wrong and now the rabbits/clones want to take over out of possibly spite/revenge. Hope you enjoyed reading this! Looking forward to the film!

text: The white rabbit omen is a symbol of death. Fertility is good luck superstition based on black rabbits. The white is the opposite. The family is not real except the boy with the burnt face. They were twins where one may have died from birth or accidental death/murder. The twin or dopplerganer superstition is that one twin is good and the other is evil. The evil has to be cast aside or burned like the a white rabbit to prevent the bad omen from happening. One superstition about the rabbit comes from the vietnamese. The tshirt that one of them has on says rabbit in Vietnamese, including the boy wearing the tshirt of the rabbit. These twins represent the bad omen of the mirror of one's self. Having a mirror at the foot of the bed is bad because you'll see yourself as a gateway to one's opposite self. Why the song I Got 5 On it? There was a 4 people in the family... but the twin boy who has the burnt face is actually the 5th who was forgotten. That's all I can think of, I could be wrong tho. Cloning could be another option, but seeing the mom separate the 2 paper figures means that the twin boys were separated before. And seeing him walk through the fire without burning gives me the death separation theory that the family could've been hiding from the boy. Look at 1:27 to see a burned child in ash.

text: In 1986, young Adelaide Thomas visits the Santa Cruz boardwalk with her parents and wanders into a house of mirrors, where she encounters her doppelganger, leaving her severely traumatized. In 2019, Adelaide (Lupita Nyong‚Äôo) reluctantly return to Santa Cruz with her husband Gabe (Winston Duke) and their children Zora and Jason to visit their friends Kitty (Elisabeth Moss) and Tyler (Tim Heidecker). After Jason nearly goes into the house of mirrors, Adelaide tells Gabe what happened to her there and demands to leave. Before they can, their doppelgangers, led by Adelaide‚Äôs double Red, break into the house and hold them hostage. Adelaide, Zora and Jason escape and go to Kitty and Tyler‚Äôs house for help, but they have already been killed by their own doppelgangers. After killing them, Adelaide finds out that the entire population of Santa Cruz has been massacred by their doubles, and decides to flee with the kids to Mexico, but Red kidnaps Jason to lure Adelaide into a confrontation at the house of mirrors. Arriving there, Adelaide ventures into a facility where the doppelgangers were held, and realizes that she is the doppelganger, and took the real Adelaide‚Äôs place when they were children. Driven insane by the isolation, the real Adelaide AKA Red has rallied the doppelgangers to escape, murder their doubles and reclaim the surface world as theirs. Adelaide kills Red after a vicious fight and rescues Jason. The movie ends with them driving away from Santa Cruz as reports of the doppelgangers rampaging across the country begin spreading.

text: SPOILER ALERT (Do not read if you haven‚Äôt seen it yet)       So here‚Äôs an explanation of what happens. When the woman was little she visited a carnival park with her parents and by accidentally wandering off she entered a little creepy room full of mirrors. There she saw a doppelg√§nger of herself, not in the mirror but in real. Now what happens after this is revealed at the end of the film. The doppelg√§nger grabbed her and pulled her into her world, which is actually underground where all the replicas (doppelg√§ngers) of all people of America live. They live here because apparently a government attempt to make clones of people went wrong so they hid them here. Then the doppelg√§nger leaves her in her place and switches places with her by wearing her clothes and entering in the outside world back to the girl‚Äôs parents. So she basically swapped places with her. Which means that‚Äôs throughout the film the woman we see is actually the doppelg√§nger who swapped places with the real one that day. And so the creepy doppelg√§nger we see in the film is actually the real girl who got swapped and trapped underground. This is why the doppelg√§nger makes vocal noises and can talk a bit while other doppelg√§ngers can‚Äôt cuz she was from the real world and knew how to talk. And this is also why she attacked the girl and her family in the real world because she wanted to take revenge from the real doppelg√§nger for ‚Äòstealing‚Äô her life by switching places with her.

text: The ‚ÄúUS‚Äù movie has a great storyline, but its direction and production are lacking. I expected to see a more compelling intro (to draw me in), similar to ‚ÄúGet Out,‚Äù where a young guy walking in an affluent neighborhood who feels out of place and scared is then suddenly kidnapped in a surprisingly scary attack. US‚Äôs ‚Äúbig moment‚Äù didn‚Äôt happen until maybe 20 minutes in. That‚Äôs where the direction failed. That ‚Äúbig moment‚Äù should have kicked off the movie rather than be delayed and supplemented with reflective moments of the main character‚Äôs past. The production should have been more generous to the art of horror and suspense rather than to the more moderate, passive ‚ÄúI got cha‚Äù moments found in most amateur horror films. The scenes needed to be more chilling. The evil antagonist should have been more sinister and menacing and each climax (peak) moment should have caught me off guard. The ‚ÄúGet out‚Äù movie had that feel. If I can predict what‚Äôs going to happen next in a movie, then you‚Äôve lost my interest and I start questioning myself as to why I even bothered to spend money to see the movie.   Overall: 3:5 Stars, It was good (okay) but could have been better; it did not reach the level of suspense of its predecessor movie ‚ÄúGet Out‚Äù   NOTE: This is just my opinion, see the movie and judge for yourself

text: For those who didn't see the movie, don't even try to assume you know what's going on.  This is a fresh movie.  Not just new, but different.  You will be giving you so many twists and turns. Then right at the very end, a plot twist.  The soundtrack was bad ass. I've been watching so many horrors movies that I know what's about to happen.  The villain popping out.  Because the score gives it away.  This here is totally different.  I'm a horror movie fan. I've been watching horror movies since the late 80's and it has been decades before I came a across a good horror movie.  Rob Zombie was good for a bit, but you get used to crazy blood and guts after the first three movies (but it's still weird when the 6'5" killer has a German accent and is in a tu-tu).  If Jordan Peele keeps up with these types of weird, strange, plot twisting horror movies. With a dope musical score. He's gonna have a horror fan base of followers.  If you like horror movies, but are tired of the same ole horror movies. Watch this movie!

text: The movie is about social class, race, and politics. Many interpretations can be drawn. The government was cloning/experimenting underground. One of the doppelgangers, Adelaide, found a way to escape, seemingly impossible because the escalator only goes down but she was able to escape and lure her human counterpart, as doppelgangers are tethered by mind and body, but not soul. This is the reason why when one act the other often do; this can be drawn from Red learning how to dance, gave birth and married in sequence, and Jason (the son) leading his doppelganger Pluto to burn in fire.  When Adelaide choked Red her vocal cords were damaged, thus the raspy voice and difficulty speaking. Adelaide, once a doppelganger couldn't speak and had to learn how to over time, thus why the parents couldn't understand why their daughter stopped talking, why Adelaide said she doesn't talk much on the beach, and when she's nervous her speech breaks. Adelaide learned to adapt in the normal world and lived a normal life; however, she always feared that Red was going to come for her, the reason she didn't want to go to the beach or was paranoid a lot. When things aligned (seen as coincident) was a sign that Red was finding ways to escape.   When Red and her family escaped, she came for revenge and to take her life back. She used the gold chained handcuffs Adelaide used to cuff her to a bed underground, then explained how miserable she was living underground and was forced to act as Adelaide did and is now coming for revenge and salvation. The movie plays out....  Analysis:   Government is experimenting or at one point experimenting. Cloning and poisoning.  A lot of 80s symbolism: Michael Jackson Thriller came out in the 80s (the thriller shirt), Hands across America (80s), Ronald Reagan's era, Nightmare on Elm street (Pluto burned skin), Friday the 13ths (the son Jason's mask), Hollween I/II (Pluto mask). Jaws: the Revenge (Gabe and Abraham fight in water, the beach, and Jason wearing the shirt). The red jumpsuit, glove, and scissors are all crossbreed of scary movies.   The children are crossbreed, both doppelgangers and human. Red is human as she was captived, eventually married and birthed children by a doppelganger. Adelaide is a doppelganger, she married and birthed children by a human. The daughter Zora showed this when she killed the twins and yelled; Jason's off the beat snapping or lack off.   The song "I got 5 on it" was chosen and remixed to give a feel of a scary movie like nightmare on elm street and the fact that it's a bay area classic along with F the police by NWA, as the film was produced in northern California.   Jason knew his mother Adelaide was a doppelganger when he witnessed her kill kitty and Red. Her screams were indicators.   Doppelgangers can be viewed as the poor class, Wilson's the middle class, and the Tyler's upper class. The poor are fighting to make their way up to middle class, middle classes are trying to compete with upper classes, and upper classes indulge and are oblivious to themselves and others.  Kitty Tyler was jealous of Adelaide beauty just as Gabe was envious of Josh. Noticed how they fought one another and how it happened. Kitty had an opportunity to kill Adelaide but instead cut her own face, Gabe killed Josh on the boat. Shows how women and men compete with each other.   Jeremiah 11:11 was a warning the Doppelgangers were coming to bring evil. Furthermore, the numbers are identical to represent 1 of you and one of me connected.  Gabe Wilson was depicted to be weak to illustrate how masculinity in America is dying.   Depicted racial tension in America" we are American " " maybe we should move to Mexico " black family chained and fighting for their lives.  Adelaide is empathetic towards the death of Zora and Jason's doppelganger because she knew those people are of her kind.  Zora and Jason's doppelgangers died the same way they were born.   The police cannot protect us; however, we can save ourselves. Reason why the cops never showed up and F the police song played (another reason for the song). Jason used the ambulance toy to stop the closet door from locking and they escaped in the ambulance.   Adelaide being chained throughout the movie depicts how blacks are still enslaved.

text: SPOILER  My interpretation on what was going on:  The government tried to control the US American people. For this they copied all citizen and had a Doppelg√§nger for everyone. The plan was that whatever the Doppelg√§ngers will do, the people on the surface will do too. But it went out to be quite the opposite (the people above controlled the people below). But what people get wrong is that the people below do NOT just copy the actions of the normal people... they adapt the purpose and the life goals of the people. Living underneath means no free chances and no life goals you might reach... so they just copy the goals of the people above and act like them. But there is a special case and that is Red and Adelaide... it is the only case where the doppelg√§nger can control the purpose of the normal person... (in a conversation original adelaide tells the fake adelaide "you know we are a special case")  Young Adelaide went down to the beach in the night during thunderstorm... I mean come on... no fucking kid would be even brave enough to do that... those actions were influenced by kid red.   But why and how does original Adelaide act completely independent from fake adelaide the whole movie... well thats pretty easy to answer and thats why the "Hands across america" thing is important.  Original Adelaide wants a revolution so she, although she lives in the underworld, has a purpose and that what makes here independent from the controls of the fake adelaide. She is the leader of the revolution and tells the others of this plan that the doppelg√§ngers first should kill their originals and then form a line starting at the beach. Now they got a meaning in their life and they act independent.  And thats what the movie is all about: free will and finding your own goals. Thats what the doppelg√§ngers want. and nobody seems to understand that from the other people above. They people above dont realize their actual privilege: free life choosing.  Hands across america is a very simple action but its all the doppelg√§ngers have in their life as a meaning and they just do it because they appreaciate their priviege now for having a free will and a meaning in their life. Something we should be thankful for. Cheers

text: This movie was absolute GARBAGE! Save your money! I loved Get Out...I am a huge horror fan, but this missed the mark! It turned into more comedy than horror...don't think that's what Jordan was going for. I am beginning to believe that critics are so desperate for something original...they jump on the "artsy," bandwagon as it being revolutionary..I.E...Warhol paints a freaking Campbell Soup logo yellow...and all of a sudden he's a genius? He was a HACK!  I want to know when people can simply make a great horror movie, without any political innuendos...and trust me...this one has a lot, but I want go there. Just disappointed. Watch any of these movies and save your money...and again...these are elements of this film, which simply rehashed what has already been done and done much better. 1. text: One of the dumbest films of recent years. Sure, it's really well made and has great moments of horror and suspense, but it makes literally zero sense, has a twist ending that negates the whole thing and about halfway through decides its characters are indestructible and can laugh in the face of any threat. There's no political or social commentary here and any attempts to read it as such only leaves the filmmakers open to accusations of being reactionary conservatives (the invisible underclass rising up, but obviously they're depicted as sub-literate murderers who want to take our stuff; talk about insulting!) It's basically an M. Night Shyamalan film that's been overrated to high heaven while Shyamalan's own work has been widely pilloried for doing the same thing to the same effect.

text: **Movie would be a lot better if the evil twins were identical.**  The evil twin would try to manipulate the real ones, and it will keep audience guessing if the characters we were looking at are the originals or not.  So many clever twist they could pull off. You could start by showing weird habit/quirk that the evil one has. For example, a side-evil looking smile, a head-tilt habit when showing a certain emotion. Or leaning on one-leg while playing with fingers, the possibilities are endless. And for the final twist, after everyone believed it was an happy-ever after, just show the quirk.   This would have made the movie at least 10x better. I really even thought the movie was gonna be like that. As in the trailer at 1:45, they said "They look exactly like us. They think like us." Because this feels more like a zombie movie. It might as well be. Only the MC's "evil twin" could talk, while the other 3 acted like zombies.   Started out like a 9.5 for me and ended like a 4/10. The twist didn't make much sense, especially with the last scene when the son was looking at her like that. The MC may be the "EVIL ONE" but she still gave birth to him and is his real mother.

text: Just watched 'Us' by Jordan Peele, and I cannot understand for one second the acclaim this guy is getting. His first movie was based on a medically impossible premise - brain transplants. Movies based on an impossible premise infuriate me. Looper by Rian Johnson for example - how could you send back a future version of yourself to be shot by you? You've already been sent back! And Get Out .. won an Oscar. And now this POS movie ... it's dumb, pointless, silly, and pretends to have a big twist at the end ... that makes absolutely no sense whatsoever given what has gone before. It's a movie about doppelgangers, but I feel like a doppelganger .. in a world full of people who think Peele is some kind of genius. Peele has now made two sub-slasher movies that make no sense and I can only conclude he was handed a career due to affirmative action. If you watch this crap it will make you question the nature of reality - not in a good way like 2001 or Ex Machina .. .but in the "What parallel universe have I landed in where this kind of shite passes for 'clever cinema'?" kind of way. Complete dog-link. Makes me lose faith in humanity.

text: Ok what I got out of this is people are only as human as you treat them, and this is a commentary on people who are treated badly in the United States (US...hint hint) through their poverty, race, ethnic group or immigration status. People who are literally "the under class." I think it also plays upon relevant fears about cloning human beings. The Hands Across America seems like a weird funny Key & Peele sort of comic relief, and it likely is partly that, but it also refers to a movement that was supposed to help the poor and homeless 30 years ago - and we still haven't solved those problems in this country, decades later.
author: Christi
